{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_fleur_ver01/data/sn83035189/00516993741/1930010901/0014.xml":{"full_text":"OHIO UNIVERSITY\nPOULTRY EXPERT\nWas the Principal Speaker\nAt Banquet Given At\nPeebles.\nPeebles, Ohio.\u2014Thanks to the gen\nerosity of Mr. and Mrs. B. R. Wright,\noole owners of the Wright Hatchery\nat Peebles, upwards of seventy-five\npersons enjoyed a sumptous chicken\ndinner in the high school gymnasium\nhere Thursday evening. The occa\nsion was a get-to-gether meeting of\npure blooded flock owners. They\nwere the guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nWright, together with a few special\nfriends from Portsmouth\u2014-adepts\nwhen it comes to sampling roasted,\nfried, stewed or baked chicken.\nFor quite a few years Mr. and Mrs.\nWright have been conducting one of\nthe best known hatcheries in the\ncountry. From a very meager plant\nat the start the hatchery now boasts\nof twin incubators of 90,000 egg ca\npacity. Chickens thus hatched have\nbeen sent to every conceivable part\nof the country. But Mr. and Mrs.\nWright are not satisfied with simply\nhatching chicks\u2014they want to im\nprove the flocks of those who furnish\nthem with eggs, and they have spared\nno expense in bringing the flocks in\nand around Peebles up to the high\nest possible standard. Only recently\nthey visited some of the finest poul\ntry farms in northern Ohio and\nMichigan and purchased more than\nSI,000 worth of pure bred cockerels,\nwhich they have placed in certain\nflocks and which will mean bigger\nand better poultry. Their one aim\nis to improve the stock, and to that\nend they have spared no expense in\ndoing their part toward accomplish\ning that end. And as a result the\nchicks they hatch find a quick mar\nket and wherever sent mean a finer\nstrain and stronger flock. Mr. and\nMrs. Wright pay a premium for the\nbest eggs\u2014and best eggs are not a\nmere chance\u2014they come from pure,\nbred stock and healthy hens. The\nhost and hostess were in their ele\nment Thursday and added much to\ntheir popularity through their\nthoughtfulness in providing a won\nderfully fine dinner and the arrang-j\ning of a program that was instruc\ntive as well as entertaining.\nThe principal address of the eve\nning was made by G. S. Vickers, a\nmember of the Ohio State University\nfaculty and one of the best versed\nprofessors in chicken lore in the en\ntire country. Plain, but always\ncourteous, he spoke for one hour and\nneedless to add his talk will do much\ntoward improving flock conditions,\nif such a thing is needed. Remarks j\nwere also made by Rev Bugett, C. A.\nWatts, Paul E. Haag, while George j\nE. Hentz, bank cashier, rendered a j\nvocal solo. Following the program i\nthree reels of motion pictures were\nshown. They were direct from the\nUnited States Agricultural depart\nment, and showed the proper care of\nchickens from the time they are\nhatched until they become producers.\nOf course, Mr. Wright was in his\nelement. He is a thorough going and\npainstaking gentleman, and the fact\nthat he and Mrs. Wright have\nmade such a wonderful success is not\nso much due to the fact they are thor\nough students of the hatchery busi\nness, but because they put their very\nlives in the undertaking and are not\nsatisfied with anything short of per\nfection.\nTRANSFERS OF REAL\nESTATE THIS WEEK\nVirgil V. Roush to Horatio Roush,\n69 acres in Sprigg township, $1.\nGeorge F. Burr to Joe Valentine,\n102% acres in Brush Creek township,\n$1.\nD. W. Reynolds to Della Busch,\n105 acres in Bratton township, $1.\nAllen and Irma White to Jonfi\nEbrite, 50 acres in Liberty town\nship, $1.\nJalia Rindig et al by Sheriff to\nSarah F. Snelling lot in Manchester,\n$2200. -v\nJohn Caraway and wife to Elmer\nW. Evans, cemetery lot in Jefferson\ntownship, $20.\nRachel Grooms, deceased to Charles\nGrooms et al, Vs interest in 162%\nacres in Tiffin township, by affidavit,\nCharles Grooms to James Wr.\nGrooms, 162% acres in Tiffin town\nship, Quit Claim Deed.\nR. L. and Pauline Henise to Forest\nj L. Grooms, 56 acres in Winchester\nI township, $1.\nThree Injured In\nHead-On Collision\nCoach And Truck\nRipley, Ohio\u2014Mr. and Mrs. Carey\nMcCoy, of Tampa, Fla., and their\ndaughter Geneva are in the Hillsboro\nhospital badly injured as the result\nof a headon automobile collision\nwhich happened Wednesday morning\nof last week about 11:30 on the A-P\nHighway just in front of the J. H.\nDonald Filling Station about three\nmiles east of Ripley.\nThe accident happened as the Mc\nCoy car, an Essex coach, was meeting\na Ford truck driven by A. C. Frump\nof Sugartree'Ridge, Highland county,\non the bend on the road at that place\nFrom the position of the cars it ap\npeared that McCoy was holding the\nwrong side of the road too closely\nand in an effort to avoid the acci\ndent, Frump skidded his wheels about\n50 feet. Both cars hit head-on and\nboth were damaged practically be\nyond repair.\nFrump escaped without injury but\nthe three in the other car suffered a\nprofusion of cuts and bruises that\nare serious, but necessarily fatal.\nThe injured trio were removed to\ntho Donald home where they were\ngiven medical attention by Dr. Robt.\nT. Prine and later were removed to\nthe hospital in the Trapp Gardner\nambulance.\nMaytag Reports Record\nBusiness for December\nThe Maytag Company, Newton,\nIowa, manufacturers of the Maytag\nAluminum Washer, reports that the\nvolume of deliveries for December,\n19?9, was one of the greatest in May\ntag history. December, which is\nnormally not a peak month, showed\na marked increase over both October\nand November and brings to a close a\nrecord breaking year for Maytag.\nThe outstanding prosperity of The\nMaytag Company is significant in\nthat their products are sold through\na sales organization of over nine\nthousand who sell direct by demon- j\nstration to the housewife. Their ex-!\nceptional sales volume reflects the.\nfundamentally sound business condi-;\ntions existing at the present time.\nThe Maytag organization is look-;\ning forward to a still larger business I\nin 1930. The business outlook is good j\nin every section of the country and i\nthe outlook in agricultural regions is\nparticularly promising.\nA Defender want Ad will locate\nwhat you want.\nCome In and See\nMy Prices\nReduced Prices On All\nSuits and\nOvercoats\nI Will Save You\nMoney\nSAM R. FREE\nHILLSBORO, OHIO\nliook\nfor it!\nLook\nfor\nit!\nTHIS sensational heatih'g\noffer again has the whole\ncountry talking.\nFor only a small down-pay\nment, you can begin enjoy\ning the whole-house comfort\nof Heatrola heating right\nnow, and not begin regular\npayments for it until next\nFail.\nHead the details of this amaz\ning offer in the January 11th\nissue of The Saturday Even\ning Post.\nThen come in and see us, or\ntelephone and invite us to\ncall at your home.\nJOHN J, BRODT SON\nAUTHORIZED DEALERS\nWEST UNION, OHIO\nEstate*\nHEATROLA\n\u25a0EATS EVERY BOOM\u2014\nPPSTAIHS AAD DOWN\nAberdeen Village\nJoint Defendant\nIn Damage Suit\nAberdeen, Ohio\u2014A damage suit\nhas been filed in the Common Pleas\nCourt at Georgetown by George M.\nBaker against the Indian Refining\nCompany and the Village or Aberdeen\nin which the plaintiff asks judgement\nin the amount of $10,000 for personal\ninjuries claimed to have been caused\nby joint negligence of the two de\nfendants. The plaintiff alleges that\nthe refining company placed a gas\noline tank in the ground on a public\nthoroughfare, but allowed a metal\npipe to project above the street and\nthat the village permitted such neg\nligent construction to exist. He\nclaims tha,t he stumbled over the\nprojecting pipe, falling to the ground,\ncausing him great personal injury,\nfor which he asks $10, 000.\nHillsboro People Injured\nIn Automobile Accident\nHillsboro, Ohio.\u2014Mrs. M. E. De\nHass had her collar bone and two ribs\nbroken Sunday when the car in which\nshe was riding went in a ditch and\nturned over. The accident occurred\non the road between Danville and\nFairview.\nWith Mrs. Dellass were Mrs.\nCharles Shields and Miss Laverne\nCochran, the latter driving the car\nwhich belonged to Charles Shields,\nMrs. Shields \"had her back wrenched\nand was l):uised. Miss Cochran was\nnot injured.\nThe woman had spent Sunday with\nrelatives near Hollowtown and were\non their way home. They had chains\non the wheels to keep the car from\nskidding. Crossing a bridge, the\nchains caught on a loose plank and\nMiss Cochran lost control of the car\nWhen it cleared the bridge it shot in\nto the ditch and turned over.\nMrs. Dellass was taken to the Hills\nboro hospital where her injuries W\u2019ere\ndressed by Dr. W. B. Rhoads.\nWell Known Aberdeen\nMan Died Last Friday\nAberdeen, Ohio.\u2014John F. Case, na\ntive of Aberdeen, died at his home\nhere Friday morning at 3 o\u2019clock. Mr.\nCase was bom June 12, 1850. He\nwas a carpenter by trade.\nMr. Case was widely known both\nin Aberdeen and Maysville and claim\ned the respect and esteem of all who\nknew him. He is survived by his\nwidow, Mrs. Jennie Case.\nFuneral services were held Sunday\nafternoon at 2 o\u2019clock from the Aber\ndeen Baptist church; interment in the\nCharter Oak Cemetery.\ni WOMAN DROWNS\n1 IN BIG SPRING\nBody of Mrs. Jno. R. Stults,\nSinking Spring, Found By\nHusband.\nMrs. John R. Stults, aged 53 years,\nwas drownded Thursday afternoon,\nDec. 25. in a big spring near their\nhome three miles west of Sinking\nSpring. The spring is enclosed in a\nbuilding and it is thought Mrs. Stults\nhad gone there to attend to some of\nher household work and slipped and\nfell in. The spring is eleven feet\ndeep and about four by six feet wide. 1\nThe body was found by her husband.\nMr. Stults had gone to the Olive\nBranch church to arrange for an en\ntertainment that was to be held there\nhis wife being at home by herself.\nDuring his absence she must have j\ngone to the spring house to get heads\nof cabbage for supper. When she\ngot the cabbage she saw a crock\nwith ice in it and went to the house\nand got a kettle of hot water to thaw\nthe ice. While during this the acci- j\ndent must have occured as the\nbroken crock and kettle were found\nnear the edge of the spring.\nOn returning home from the i\nchurch Mr. Stults stopped at the\nspring house. He saw something\nfloating on top of the water and at\ntempted to fish it out with a pole.\nWith the pole he pulled the body of\nhis wife to the surface and managed\nto get her out of the water.\nHe called a physician at once and\nnotifitd his neighbors. Mr. Stulls\nthought his wife was still breathing\nwhen he took her from the pool but\nthe physician is of the opinion that\nshe was dead at the time.\nThe Stults live on what is known\nas the George Davidson farm and\neleven years ago Isaac Davidson was\ndrowned in this same spring.\nThe furneral services were held on\nSunday at Olive Branch church, con\nducted by Rev Armon Cheek of Mans\nfield. Burial was made in the Olive\nBranch cemetery. Mrs. Stults is sur\nvived by her husband and one brother\nCharles Bobb.\nCars Badly Wrecked\nBut Nobody Injured\nManchester, Ohio. When Mrs.\nPercy Doddridge was driving her\nBuick sedan to Portsmouth Wednes\nday afternoon of last week, a flat tire\ncaused the car to act up in such a\nmanner that it was badly wrecked.\nThe occupants, Evelyn and Juanita\nGrimes, Mary Thompson, Eleanor\nLang, Alice Helen and Tommy Dod\ndridge and Mrs. Doddridge, escaped\ninjury The car was towed to a\ngarage.\nRead the Defender Classified Ads.\nReport of the Condition\nOF\u2014\nTHE FARMERS\u2019 BANK i\nSAVINGS CO.\nPEEBLES, OHIO\nAt the close of Business December 31st, 1929.\nRESOURCES I\nLoans on Real Estate 71,976.85\nLoans on Collateral 10,700.00\nOther Loans and Discounts 241,898.83\nOverdrafts 472.19\nIT. S. Bonds and Securities 500.00\nState, County and Municipal Bonds 72,774.62\nOther Bonds, Stoeks and Securities 71.8-12.50 I\nBanking House and Lot 3,500.00\nFurniture and Fixtures 3,000.00\nReal Estate udher than Banking\